background_dashed.customLabel: In Pre-school (<6 years old),  participants, there is a small-to-moderate effect in favor of DIET on Overall ASD symptoms. Based on the analysis of the quality of the evidence produced by the 7 clinical trials exploring this effect, we have a very low confidence in the estimation of this effect.

In School-age (6-12 years old),  participants, there is a small-to-moderate effect in favor of DIET on Overall ASD symptoms. Based on the analysis of the quality of the evidence produced by the 4 clinical trials exploring this effect, we have a very low confidence in the estimation of this effect.

In School-age (6-12 years old),  participants, there is a small-to-moderate effect in favor of DIET on Restricted/repetitive behaviors. Based on the analysis of the quality of the evidence produced by the 5 clinical trials exploring this effect, we have a very low confidence in the estimation of this effect.

In Pre-school (<6 years old),  participants, there is no difference between DIET and controls on Social-communication. Based on the analysis of the quality of the evidence produced by the 5 clinical trials exploring this effect, we have a very low confidence in the estimation of this effect.

In Pre-school (<6 years old),  participants, there is a small-to-moderate effect in favor of DIET on Global cognition (IQ). Based on the analysis of the quality of the evidence produced by the 3 clinical trials exploring this effect, we have a very low confidence in the estimation of this effect.
